SOC Detection Pack Home Lab  

This is structured like a real blue team detection set:

Endpoint (Sysmon)
Identity (logons / brute force)
Execution (PowerShell / LOLBins)
Persistence
Defense evasion
Malware signals (Defender)

- PowerShell Attack Detection (High Value)

<rule id="100100" level="12">
  <if_group>windows,sysmon</if_group>
  <field name="win.eventdata.image">powershell.exe</field>
  <description>Suspicious PowerShell execution detected</description>
</rule>

- LOLBins Detection (Living off the Land)

<rule id="100200" level="10">
  <if_group>windows,sysmon</if_group>
  <field name="win.eventdata.image">certutil.exe</field>
  <description>Suspicious use of certutil (possible download/exfil tool)</description>
</rule>

- Process Injection / Suspicious Parent-Child

<rule id="100300" level="12">
  <if_group>windows,sysmon</if_group>
  <field name="win.eventdata.parentImage">winword.exe</field>
  <field name="win.eventdata.image">powershell.exe</field>
  <description>Office spawning PowerShell (possible macro attack)</description>
</rule>

- RDP Brute Force Detection

<rule id="100400" level="10">
  <if_sid>60122</if_sid>
  <match>4625</match>
  <description>Multiple failed login attempts (possible brute force)</description>
</rule>

- Sysmon File Creation (Persistence Detection)

<rule id="100500" level="12">
  <if_group>windows,sysmon</if_group>
  <field name="win.eventdata.targetFilename">*\\Startup\\*</field>
  <description>File created in Startup folder (persistence attempt)</description>
</rule>

- DLL Hijacking / Injection (You already saw this)

<rule id="100600" level="13">
  <if_group>windows,sysmon_eid11_detections</if_group>
  <description>Possible DLL hijacking / side-loading activity</description>
</rule>

- Suspicious Network Activity (Sysmon EID 3)

<rule id="100700" level="10">
  <if_group>windows,sysmon</if_group>
  <field name="win.eventdata.destinationIp">!192.168.*</field>
  <description>Outbound connection to external IP (possible beaconing)</description>
</rule>

- Privilege Escalation Signals

<rule id="100800" level="12">
  <if_group>windows,sysmon</if_group>
  <field name="win.eventdata.user">NT AUTHORITY\\SYSTEM</field>
  <description>System-level process execution (monitor for escalation)</description>
</rule>


SOC Dashboard Queries
- High severity events
  rule.level >= 10

- Sysmon attack surface
  rule.groups:sysmon AND rule.level >= 6

- Windows attack behavior
  rule.groups:windows AND rule.level >= 8

